Fleshy & yellow gape.  Singing and Intimating calls & songs of other birds from water melon crops ( there were also weeds which covered those crops, so it was suitable habitat for this bird). Song is sweet with wonderful mimicry. Habitat photographed. Call & Song records available. More individuals may present in those crop.  It was previously known from basur kaval & its surroundings near basur ( https://ebird.org/checklist/S51988206 ).

Locality: Mula river, Pimple Nilakh Crematorium side, Pimpri Chinchwad IN-Maharashtra (18.5683,73.7977)
Media notes: A pair was seen calling. Pair calls last for much of the clip’s duration. By the end of the clip, after one of them flew away, only a single bird can be heard.
Observation Details: Two Clamorous Reed Warblers were observed actively using the dense riverbank vegetation, flying between both banks while vocalizing. Their calls were noted up close when they perched on a tree, with one individual hopping from the middle of the tree to the top canopy while calling. Shortly after it stopped vocalizing, it took flight, and the second bird quickly followed. This species appears significantly larger than the similarly coloured Blyth’s Reed Warbler and even seems bigger than a House Sparrow in size when seen in the field. Its vocalization is much louder than that of Blyth’s Reed Warbler or any other similar warblers, making it far more prominent in the field.

Behaviors: Foraging or Eating; Preening, Scratching, or Bathing; Song
Observation Details: Better views than the previous day right at eye level; seems to be quite common in the area! A nesting pair using a hole in a tree right next to the dam, and another male seen in the nearby forest. Details on the nesting behaviour (hope it aids our understanding of the species) I first noticed the rufous-bellied male calling and foraging (or seeming to do so at the very least, assuming me to be a potential predator) in the trees nearby the nest. Sometimes later, I noticed the female plastering the walls of a rather low-lying (some 8-11 feet above ground) and quite wide tree hole with mud, while the male remained nearby; standing guard and calling. The pair was quite reclusive and retreated to the trees on the other side of the dam while giving the typical flight call when approached closely, only to return after we had backed down some distance away.
